vcpkg-sample-library provides CMake targets:

## Basic Usage

Add to your CMakeLists.txt:
\`\`\`cmake
find_package(my_sample_lib CONFIG REQUIRED)
target_link_libraries(main PRIVATE my_sample_lib::my_sample_lib)
\`\`\`

## Example Project

### CMakeLists.txt
\`\`\`cmake
cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.10)
project(sample_app)

find_package(my_sample_lib CONFIG REQUIRED)

add_executable(sample_app main.cpp)
target_link_libraries(sample_app PRIVATE my_sample_lib::my_sample_lib)
\`\`\`

### main.cpp
\`\`\`cpp
#include <my_sample_lib/hello.hpp>

int main() {
    my_sample_lib::say_hello();
    return 0;
}
\`\`\`

**Note:** The \`say_hello()\` function outputs "Hello, helloworld!"

## Building with vcpkg

\`\`\`bash
# Install the library
vcpkg install vcpkg-sample-library

# Configure your project
cmake -B build -S . -DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE=$VCPKG_ROOT/scripts/buildsystems/vcpkg.cmake

# Build
cmake --build build
\`\`\`

## Notes

- This library depends on fmt for string formatting
- Only static library linkage is supported
- The library provides a simple hello world function as a demonstration
